the nation, engaging themselves politically and creating a cross-cultural dialogue between journalism and fiction. Early in this century, writers such as Zitkala-Sa, Mourning Dove, Alice Dunbar-Nelson, and Anzia Yezierska developed their writing careers through affiliations with reform organizations. They worked for Pan-Indianism, racial uplift, immigrant aid, or social welfare. Carol Batker explores the impact of their journalism and political work on their fiction. She demonstrates points of contact among these women that suggest mutual influence and conversations across racial and ethnic lines-revealing important historical antecedents to contemporary debates about multiculturalism in America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aAmerican fictionx20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican fictionxWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican fictionxWomen authors. 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican prose literaturexMinority authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican prose literaturexMinority authors. 0aJournalismzUnited StatesxHistoryx20th century. 0aJournalismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial problemszUnited StatesxHistoryx20th century. 0aSocial problemszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryx20th century. 0aWomen and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen in journalismzUnited StatesxHistoryx20th century. 0aWomen in journalismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen social reformerszUnited States. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Women Authors.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066254208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247208iTitle is par